{"author":{"id":"b78c39e7b13f90a5827abfba043255fe7a4ede1499df23f110fffe5abfa44adc"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1770993534,"nonce":"B0UMoxL4zpcrBRZXvHNsmyJQrRc=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOQ241x87qsXyJ","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/198","origin":"github"},"title":"make setup-dev not part of bootstrap flow; pre-commit hooks can be silently missing","message":"## Problem\n\n`make setup-dev` (which creates the `.venv`, installs pre-commit, and runs `pre-commit install`) is a manual step that can be forgotten after a fresh clone. The bootstrap and health-check scripts don't ensure it's been run, and CONTRIBUTING.md doesn't mention it in the getting-started steps.\n\nThis means a developer or AI agent can clone, bootstrap, build, and start committing **without any pre-commit hooks active** — bypassing shellcheck, black/flake8/pylint, commit identity validation, and branch status checks.\n\n### How this was discovered\n\nAn agent's `make setup-dev` was run from inside a worktree (issue-190), which pointed `.git/hooks/pre-commit` at that worktree's ephemeral `.venv`. When the worktree was removed, the hook broke — but the deeper issue is that the hook setup isn't part of the standard bootstrap flow and isn't validated by health checks.\n\n## Proposed changes\n\n1. **`health_check.sh`**: Add a check for `.venv/bin/pre-commit` existence and whether `pre-commit install` has been run (i.e., `.git/hooks/pre-commit` exists and points to a valid Python). Warn if missing.\n\n2. **CONTRIBUTING.md**: Add `make setup-dev` as an explicit step in the \"Getting Started\" section.\n\n3. **`bootstrap.sh`** (optional): Either call `make setup-dev` at the end, or print a reminder message like:\n   ```\n   Next step: run 'make setup-dev' to install pre-commit hooks\n   ```\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null}]}